## Next: API Plan (high level)

Goal: Laravel server (separate machine) can create/disable/enable/export clients via a secure API on Server-1.

Recommended approach:
1) Server-1: nginx reverse proxy with mTLS on port 443, proxying to a local agent on 127.0.0.1.
2) Agent exposes minimal endpoints and executes `awgctl`:
   - `POST /v1/create {name}` -> runs `awgctl create --name <name>` and returns config (or returns an ID, and client downloads via export).
   - `POST /v1/disable {name|pubkey}`
   - `POST /v1/enable {name|pubkey}`
   - `GET /v1/export?name=...` -> returns decrypted config (or pre-signed one-time URL)
   - `GET /v1/status?name=...` -> parses `awg show`
   - `GET /v1/health` -> checks xray/dnsmasq/iptables/awg0

Security notes:
- Do not expose agent without mTLS and (optionally) IP allowlist.
- PrivateKey delivery should be one-time where possible.
- If you keep encrypted configs server-side, protect `/etc/awgctl/master.pass` (600, root-only) and back it up securely.
